<subSubSection lastPageId="77" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1726,2023]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1726,1752]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Remarks.</emphasis>
Opercular talons as reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pillai, T. G." box="[723,865,1726,1752]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="110 - 177" refId="ref65891" refString="Pillai, T. G. (1965) Annelida polychaeta from the Philippines and Indonesia. Ceylon Journal of Science (Biological Science), 5, 110 - 177." type="journal article" year="1965">Pillai (1965</bibRefCitation>
fig. 22H) and ten 
<bibRefCitation author="Hove, H. A. ten" box="[1097,1240,1726,1752]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="1 - 21" refId="ref60604" refString="Hove, H. A. ten (1973) Serpulinae (Polychaeta) from the Caribbean: II - the genus Sclerostyla. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands, 43, 1 - 21." type="journal article" year="1973">Hove (1973</bibRefCitation>
fig. 43) are not consistenly mentioned (nor looked for) in the literature. Whether or not the presence of such a talon is a character distinguishing between populations or even taxa should be investigated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1726,2023]" lastBlockId="77.[151,1436,152,216]" lastPageId="77" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Baird" baseAuthorityYear="1865" box="[198,447,1842,1867]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoleios" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[198,447,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Pomatoleios kraussii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in the Indo-Pacific forming intertidal aggregations. The only difference between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1844" box="[384,537,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[384,537,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Pomatoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pixell" authorityYear="1913" box="[597,743,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoleios" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[597,743,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Pomatoleios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the more or less consistent lack of collar chaetae in the latter. However, collar chaetae may be present in juvenile specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="Zibrowius, H." box="[968,1172,1920,1946]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="81 - 252" refId="ref69212" refString="Zibrowius, H. (1968 a) Etude morphologique, systematique et ecologique des Serpulidae (Annelida Polychaeta) de la region de Marseille. Recueil des Traveaux de la Station Marine d'Endoume, Bulletin 43, 81 - 252." type="journal article" year="1968">Zibrowius 1968a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Crisp, M." box="[1185,1317,1920,1946]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="147 - 160" refId="ref57568" refString="Crisp, M. (1977) The development of the serpulid Pomatoleios kraussii (Annelida, Polychaeta). Journal of Zoology, London, 183, 147 - 160." type="journal article" year="1977">Crisp 1977</bibRefCitation>
, ten 
<bibRefCitation author="Hove, H. A. ten &amp; Nishi, E." pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="83 - 96" refId="ref61205" refString="Hove, H. A. ten &amp; Nishi, E. (1996) A redescription of the Indo-West Pacific Spirobranchus corrugatus Straughan, 1967 (Serpulidae, Polychaeta), and an alternative hypothesis on the nature of a group of Middle Miocene microfossils from Poland. Beaufortia, 46, 83 - 96." type="journal article" year="1996">
Hove &amp; 
<collectingRegion box="[183,246,1958,1984]" country="Serbia" name="Nis" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Nishi</collectingRegion>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
), and occasionally absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1844" box="[667,820,1958,1983]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[667,820,1958,1983]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Pomatoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<specimenCount box="[899,1046,1958,1984]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="generic">9 specimens</specimenCount>
from the Irish Sea, ZMA V.Pol. 3201) as well as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Blainville" authorityYear="1818" box="[379,551,1997,2022]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Spirobranchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[379,551,1997,2022]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Spirobranchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., as 
<taxonomicName authority="Jones, 1962" authorityName="Jones" authorityYear="1962" box="[656,1033,1997,2023]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Olga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="elegantissima">
<emphasis box="[656,884,1997,2022]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Olga elegantissima</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, M. L." box="[891,1033,1997,2023]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="169 - 212" refId="ref62387" refString="Jones, M. L. (1962) On some polychaetous annelids from Jamaica, the West Indies. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, New York, 124, 5, 169 - 212." type="journal article" year="1962">Jones, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), thus this monotypic genus likely lacks a phylogenetic basis. See further remarks for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Blainville" authorityYear="1818" box="[753,924,152,177]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Spirobranchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[753,924,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Spirobranchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. SEM photos of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pixell" authorityYear="1913" box="[1124,1270,152,177]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoleios" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1270,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Pomatoleios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are published in 
<bibRefCitation author="Fiege, D. &amp; Sun, R." box="[181,418,190,216]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" pagination="109 - 141" refId="ref58676" refString="Fiege, D. &amp; Sun, R. (1999) Polychaeta from Hainan Island, South China Sea Part I: Serpulidae. Seckenbergiana Biologia, 79, 109 - 141." type="journal article" year="1999">Fiege &amp; Sun (1999)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[151,1436,268,332]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName authority="(Baird, 1865)" baseAuthorityName="Baird" baseAuthorityYear="1865" box="[151,569,268,294]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Pomatoleios" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[151,399,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Pomatoleios kraussii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Baird, W." box="[415,559,268,294]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" pagination="10 - 22" refId="ref55785" refString="Baird, W. (1865) Description of several new species and varieties of tubicolous annelides = Tribe Limivora of Grube, in the collection of the British Museum. I &amp; II. Journal of the Linnean Society, London (Zoology), 8, 10 - 22." type="journal article" year="1865">Baird, 1865</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[582,737,268,294]" name="South Africa" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">South Africa</collectingCountry>
; widely distributed in the Indo-Pacific; Lessepsian migrant to the Levant Mediterranean.
</paragraph>
